<font color="#FF0000">DIFFERENCES</font><br>
<tt>Mon May 19  6:34:57 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Clifton, thanks you for your thanks.  That is all many of us really want.  Recognition of our efforts.  Not the results.  Many went after the warriors and failed to see at the time that it was our government policy and lack of leadership that created all the legacies of Vietnam.<br>
The primary difference between WW2 vets and Vietnam vets was the opportunity to discuss their time in battle with their peers. Transportation for the most part was surface, i.e. ships, and the time it took to return to the states enabled them to process a lot of the issues involved in combat.  My story was on May 26, 1967 I was in a forward firebase and on May 27, 1967 I was walking the streets of Portland, Oregon.  I went by myself and came home by myself.  No time for processing my experiences or my grief.<br>
Another factor involved was age.  The average age of the WWII vet was 26 and the average age of the Nam vet was 19.  A little less maturity.  So many stories center around the statement; &quot;I went over a 18 tear old boy and returned as a 50 year old man.&quot;  
